title: For Sale:  obo Henry AR-7 survival rifle with heavy barrel, rings, holster, case, mags, original barrel, box, etc
postcontent:
For additional pics go here:
http://s78.photobucket.com/user/triton_23/slideshow/AR-7
NOTE: There is a scope in part of one photo, but this sale does not include a scope.

This is an AR-7 survival rifle. They have been manufactured for years by multiple companies.
The gun disassembles VERY easily (no tools) and can be stored inside the waterproof stock.
When fully sealed, you can leave it in your boat or other dangerous/wet location. Not only will it stay dry, it supposedly floats.

This gun, like most .22's is highly accurate.

But one problem with the stock gun is a thin barrel that needs to be chamfered so ammo can feed directly and cleanly off the feed ramp.
This replacement barrel is much heavier, and is nicely chamfered. 
The additional weight allows a much easier hold (otherwise it can feel like you are aiming a pencil, because it's so light). It will also last much longer, and due to thickness, stays cooler than the stock barrel.

The barrel came from AR-7 Customized Accessories
http://ar7.imoutdoorshosting.com/store/AR7barrels.html

The auction DOES include the original barrel, as well as the heavy barrel. If you want to use this in its survival form, you will have to use the original barrel because the heavy barrel does not fit in the stock.

I also have some extra magazines, but be wary of 3rd party magazines. Ideal for size are the 30 round because they allow you to hold the magazine like a forward grip.
But aftermarket AR-7 magazines have notorious feed issues, so you should try to get Henry mags or dealers which guarantee their product.

I actually have a holster for this rifle! 

In the pictures, you will notice some electrical tape on the stock which is there to thicken the butt and create a very tight seal. It is not covering any blemishes or defects.
The second piece of tape inside the butt contains the original (pain in the ass) screw for the sight.

I also replaced the annoying rear sight (stock) screw with a thumb screw that can be manipulated by hand, or with the hex key in the stock.

You also get the soft carry case. It's one of the smallest rifle cases made, and is a bit large, but you can fold over the top and tighten it down using the strap, which makes it a good size.
Or use it for your other rifles/shotguns.

I left the 1" rings mounted to the weapon because I can't use them for any of my other guns. They are yours to keep!

I like this gun, but don't need it any more as I moved into the city (no shooting varmints) and have two other .22's. 
I unfortunately don't have a boat, either.

Check out my other auctions. 
I'm somewhat willing to drive for this auction--StL, KC, Spfld, or Lamar--we might be able to work something out.

PAYMENT:
If paying by check of any kind, we will wait fully for payment to complete/deposit before finishing the transaction. This includes cashier's checks and money orders.
Paypal and bitcoin accepted.

title: For Sale:  obo 26.5mm Polish flare pistol WITH FLARES, holster, 12 ga insert
postcontent:
** NO TRADES **

This steel WW II flare pistol is probably Polish. It was sold to me as a Walther, but it is definitely not a Walther.

I have fired it once, and it works--unsurprisingly as it is incredibly simple, and is heavy steel. 

It comes with a fantastic vintage leather holster for holding the gun and several flares. I believe it holds 4 on top and 6 in the bottom, but flare length varies.
Note that it is all leather and not canvas like all the flare pouches I have seen.
This is the "official" holster for the pistol, it is made just to hold this flare gun and flares and is not a repurposed bag, holster, satchel, etc.

I also have (I believe) 19 flares, two boxes of 10 with one shot to verify that they work. 
It looks like one box is white parachute and one box is single flare red.
I think I fired the red flare, so this should be 9 red and 10 white.
The flares appear to be Czech, I don't recall where I got them, only that they were imported Eastern European surplus.

Flares are a huge pain in the ass to get shipped, these are far harder to obtain than the flare gun. The flare gun does not require an FFA license for mailing/transfer.

There is a 12 gauge aluminum insert so that you can fire standard flares which are easily obtained.

Check out my other auctions. 
http://www.armslist.com/classifieds/search?relatedto=4468868

I'm somewhat willing to drive for this auction--StL, KC, Spfld, or Lamar--we might be able to work something out.

PAYMENT:
If paying by check of any kind, we will wait fully for payment to complete/deposit before finishing the transaction. This includes cashier's checks and money orders.
Paypal and bitcoin accepted.
